^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Very nice mei ann. First let's talk about whether sacrificing was a good idea with the E/W cards and how to judge. Actually, 5 clubs is only down 1 as it turns out, but that is hard to know. The three main criteria for deciding if a sacrifice is good are:
a) lots of trump length, 10 cards preferably which they have,
b) shortness in the opponents suit (singleton or void), which they don't have, and
c) of course vulnerability.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me explain from a scoring perspective when it is a good sacrifice. At equal vulnerability, if you go down 1 or 2, it is a good sacrifice. That is because game is worth 420 non vul/620 vul, more or less. Down 2 doubled is 300 non vul/ and 500 vul. If both nonvul, down 3 is not horrible in IMPs, because you are losing 500 instead of 420. But in match points it is a disaster. At favorable vul (you are, they are not), then down 3 is fine because you are -500 vs. -620 for their game. At unfavorable vul (you are they are not) sacrifices are very rare, as you can only afford to go down 1 (-200 vs - 420).|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let us talk about Marge's bid. 3C was okay, but a better bid would be a 2S cue bid. Although she happens to have spade cards on this hand, 2S does not say anything about spades. It shows a limit raise in clubs, and that's what Marge has. That might help Ginny decide whether or not to sacrifice. Frankly, I am not sure I would sacrifice with either of their hands. With a doubleton heart, and AK in a side suit, I might think there is a better chance of beating them and more chance we will go down too many.. So, I might very well decide not to bid 5C with either hand.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also as Ginny suggested, let us use what is known as "Losing Trick Count" to help decide as well without getting into a lot of detail (you can look at my introduction to constructive bidding movie for details). Ginny has 7 losers and a limit raise (by Marge) tends to show an 8 loser hand. They have a combined 15 loser hand from Ginny's perspective had Marge bid a limit raise. The way losing trick count works, you subtract your losers from 24 to determine your winners--9 winers (24-15). So, the 5C sacrifice bid is down 2 doubled which is close as to whether to sacrifice or not. LTC is a guide, but is not always completely accurate. I could go either way using LTC.|
